answers.body_markdown:
This seems like an infinite loop:
```
databaseReference.addValueEventListener(new ValueEventListener() {
    @Override
    public void onDataChange(@NonNull DataSnapshot snapshot) {
        databaseReference.push().setValue(userDetails);

    }

    @Override
    public void onCancelled(@NonNull DatabaseError error) {

    }
});
```

---

Calling `addValueEventListener` registers a persistent, realtime listener on `databaseReference`. From the documentation on [reading data with persistent listeners](https://firebase.google.com/docs/database/android/read-and-write#read_data_with_persistent_listeners):

&gt; **Important**: The onDataChange() method is called every time data is changed at the specified database reference

And:

&gt; This method is triggered once when the listener is attached and again every time the data, including children, changes.

So your `onDataChange` gets called with the data from `databaseReference` immediately, and in there you add new data to `databaseReference` by calling `push().setValue(userDetails)` on it. This in turn then triggers the `onDataChange` again, and you again write a new child to it. This continues indefinitely, until the app is closed.

---

Nothing in what you shared requires the `addValueEventListener` as far as I can see, so you can replace that entire block with:
```
databaseReference.push().setValue(userDetails);
```

